When Caesar was forty-two years old-that ic, in the year 58 s.c.,—he set out for Gaul, ostensibly for the purpose of pro tecting Roman territory, but as the event showed, for the sub jugationes the land. In nine years he subdued the whole of Gaul and converted it into a Roman province. In the cam· paigns of these nine years he disciplined and attached to himself an army which afterward made him the master of Rome. The first Gallic people which Caesar encountered were the Helvetii, the inhabitants of modern Switzerland. The Helvetii thought their country was too small, and besides were harassed by the neigh- boring tribes of Germany, and so resolved to seek wider limite and a more peaceful honre to the west, on the borders of the ocean.
